<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, <b>linear regression</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_model" title=3D"Statistical model">model</a> t=
hat estimates the relationship between a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Scalar_(mathematics)" title=3D"Scalar (mathematics)">scalar</a> resp=
onse (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dependent_variable" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dependent variable">dependent variable</a>) and one =
or more explanatory variables (<b>regressor</b> or <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Independent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Indep=
endent variable">independent variable</a>). A model with exactly one explan=
atory variable is a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_line=
ar_regression" title=3D"Simple linear regression">simple linear regression<=
/a></i>; a model with two or more explanatory variables is a <b>multiple li=
near regression</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Freedman-2009_1-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Fr=
eedman-2009-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> This term is distinct from <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_linear_regression" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Multivariate linear regression">multivariate linear regression</a>, =
which predicts multiple <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlated=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Correlated">correlated</a> dependent varia=
bles rather than a single dependent variable.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#c=
ite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In linear regression, the relationships are modeled using <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_predictor_function" title=3D"Linear p=
redictor function">linear predictor functions</a> whose unknown model <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parameters" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Parameters">parameters</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Estimation_theory" title=3D"Estimation theory">estimated</a> from the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data" title=3D"Data">data</a>. Most co=
mmonly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_mean" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Conditional mean">conditional mean</a> of the re=
sponse given the values of the explanatory variables (or predictors) is ass=
umed to be an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affine_function" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Affine function">affine function</a> of those v=
alues; less commonly, the conditional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Median" title=3D"Median">median</a> or some other <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantile" title=3D"Quantile">quantile</a> is used. Like=
 all forms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis"=
 title=3D"Regression analysis">regression analysis</a>, linear regression f=
ocuses on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_probabil=
ity_distribution" title=3D"Conditional probability distribution">conditiona=
l probability distribution</a> of the response given the values of the pred=
ictors, rather than on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_p=
robability_distribution" title=3D"Joint probability distribution">joint pro=
bability distribution</a> of all of these variables, which is the domain of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_analysis" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Multivariate analysis">multivariate analysis</a>.
</p><p>Linear regression is also a type of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"Machine learning">machine learning</a> =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">alg=
orithm</a>, more specifically a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Su=
pervised_learning" title=3D"Supervised learning">supervised</a> algorithm, =
that learns from the labelled datasets and maps the data points to the most=
 optimized linear functions that can be used for prediction on new datasets=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Linear regression was the first type of regression analysis to be st=
udied rigorously, and to be used extensively in practical applications.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is because models which=
 depend linearly on their unknown parameters are easier to fit than models =
which are non-linearly related to their parameters and because the statisti=
cal properties of the resulting estimators are easier to determine.
</p><p>Linear regression has many practical uses. Most applications fall in=
to one of the following two broad categories:
</p>
<ul><li>If the goal is to reduce error, i.e. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Variance_reduction" title=3D"Variance reduction">variance</a> in=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prediction" title=3D"Prediction">=
prediction</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forecasting" tit=
le=3D"Forecasting">forecasting</a>, linear regression can be used to fit a =
predictive model to an observed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Da=
ta_set" title=3D"Data set">data set</a> of values of the response and expla=
natory variables. After developing such a model, if additional values of th=
e explanatory variables are collected without an accompanying response valu=
e, the fitted model can be used to make a prediction of the response.</li>
<li>If the goal is to explain variation in the response variable that can b=
e attributed to variation in the explanatory variables, linear regression a=
nalysis can be applied to quantify the strength of the relationship between=
 the response and the explanatory variables, and in particular to determine=
 whether some explanatory variables may have no linear relationship with th=
e response at all, or to identify which subsets of explanatory variables ma=
y contain redundant information about the response.</li></ul>
<p>Linear regression models are often fitted using the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_squares" title=3D"Least squares">least squares</=
a> approach, but they may also be fitted in other ways, such as by minimizi=
ng the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodness_of_fit" title=3D"=
Goodness of fit">lack of fit</a>" in some other <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Norm_(mathematics)" title=3D"Norm (mathematics)">norm</a> (as=
 with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_absolute_deviations" t=
itle=3D"Least absolute deviations">least absolute deviations</a> regression=
), or by minimizing a penalized version of the least squares <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loss_function" title=3D"Loss function">cost func=
tion</a> as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ridge_regression" t=
itle=3D"Ridge regression">ridge regression</a> (<i>L</i><sup>2</sup>-norm p=
enalty) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lasso_(statistics)" ti=
tle=3D"Lasso (statistics)">lasso</a> (<i>L</i><sup>1</sup>-norm penalty). U=
se of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_Squared_Error" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mean Squared Error">Mean Squared Error</a> (MSE)=
 as the cost on a dataset that has many large outliers, can result in a mod=
el that fits the outliers more than the true data due to the higher importa=
nce assigned by MSE to large errors. So, cost functions that are robust to =
outliers should be used if the dataset has many large <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huber_loss" title=3D"Huber loss">outliers</a>. Converse=
ly, the least squares approach can be used to fit models that are not linea=
r models. Thus, although the terms "least squares" and "linear model" are c=
losely linked, they are not synonymous.
</p>
