<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Assumptions">Assumptions</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regress=
ion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Assumptions">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_least_squares#A=
ssumptions" title=3D"Ordinary least squares">Ordinary least squares =C2=A7&=
nbsp;Assumptions</a></div>
<p>Standard linear regression models with standard estimation techniques ma=
ke a number of assumptions about the predictor variables, the response vari=
able and their relationship. Numerous extensions have been developed that a=
llow each of these assumptions to be relaxed (i.e. reduced to a weaker form=
), and in some cases eliminated entirely. Generally these extensions make t=
he estimation procedure more complex and time-consuming, and may also requi=
re more data in order to produce an equally precise model.<sup class=3D"nop=
rint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wik=
ipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to relia=
ble sources. (February 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Polyreg_scheffe.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b=
/Polyreg_scheffe.svg/500px-Polyreg_scheffe.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" widt=
h=3D"380" height=3D"253" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"540" =
data-file-height=3D"360"></a><figcaption>Example of a cubic polynomial regr=
ession, which is a type of linear regression. Although <i>polynomial regres=
sion</i> fits a curve model to the data, as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Estimation_theory" title=3D"Estimation theory">statistical esti=
mation</a> problem it is linear, in the sense that the regression function =
E(<i>y</i> | <i>x</i>) is linear in the unknown <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Parameter" title=3D"Parameter">parameters</a> that are estima=
ted from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data" title=3D"Data">=
data</a>. For this reason, polynomial regression is considered to be a spec=
ial case of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_linear_regres=
sion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multiple linear regression">multiple l=
inear regression</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The following are the major assumptions made by standard linear regressi=
on models with standard estimation techniques (e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_least_squares" title=3D"Ordinary least squares">=
ordinary least squares</a>):
</p>
<ul><li><b>Weak exogeneity</b>. This essentially means that the predictor v=
ariables <i>x</i> can be treated as fixed values, rather than <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">rand=
om variables</a>. This means, for example, that the predictor variables are=
 assumed to be error-free=E2=80=94that is, not contaminated with measuremen=
t errors. Although this assumption is not realistic in many settings, dropp=
ing it leads to significantly more difficult <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Errors-in-variables_models" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Error=
s-in-variables models">errors-in-variables models</a>.</li>
<li><b>Linearity</b>. This means that the mean of the response variable is =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_combination" title=3D"Lin=
ear combination">linear combination</a> of the parameters (regression coeff=
icients) and the predictor variables. Note that this assumption is much les=
s restrictive than it may at first seem. Because the predictor variables ar=
e treated as fixed values (see above), linearity is really only a restricti=
on on the parameters. The predictor variables themselves can be arbitrarily=
 transformed, and in fact multiple copies of the same underlying predictor =
variable can be added, each one transformed differently. This technique is =
used, for example, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_r=
egression" title=3D"Polynomial regression">polynomial regression</a>, which=
 uses linear regression to fit the response variable as an arbitrary <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynom=
ial</a> function (up to a given degree) of a predictor variable. With this =
much flexibility, models such as polynomial regression often have "too much=
 power", in that they tend to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Over=
fit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Overfit">overfit</a> the data. As a res=
ult, some kind of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regularization_(=
mathematics)" title=3D"Regularization (mathematics)">regularization</a> mus=
t typically be used to prevent unreasonable solutions coming out of the est=
imation process. Common examples are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Ridge_regression" title=3D"Ridge regression">ridge regression</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lasso_regression" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Lasso regression">lasso regression</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_linear_regression" title=3D"Bayesian linear reg=
ression">Bayesian linear regression</a> can also be used, which by its natu=
re is more or less immune to the problem of overfitting. (In fact, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ridge_regression" title=3D"Ridge regressi=
on">ridge regression</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lasso=
_regression" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lasso regression">lasso regress=
ion</a> can both be viewed as special cases of Bayesian linear regression, =
with particular types of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prior_dis=
tribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prior distribution">prior distrib=
utions</a> placed on the regression coefficients.)</li>
<li><figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Heteroscedasticity_in_Linear_Regression.p=
ng" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/=
wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Heteroscedasticity_in_Linear_Regression.png/33=
0px-Heteroscedasticity_in_Linear_Regression.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"300" height=3D"238" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"626" d=
ata-file-height=3D"496"></a><figcaption>Visualization of heteroscedasticity=
 in a scatter plot against 100 random fitted values using Matlab</figcaptio=
n></figure><b>Constant variance</b> (a.k.a. <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Homoscedasticity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Homoscedastic=
ity">homoscedasticity</a></b>). This means that the variance of the errors =
does not depend on the values of the predictor variables. Thus the variabil=
ity of the responses for given fixed values of the predictors is the same r=
egardless of how large or small the responses are. This is often not the ca=
se, as a variable whose mean is large will typically have a greater varianc=
e than one whose mean is small. For example, a person whose income is predi=
cted to be $100,000 may easily have an actual income of $80,000 or $120,000=
=E2=80=94i.e., a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviatio=
n" title=3D"Standard deviation">standard deviation</a> of around $20,000=E2=
=80=94while another person with a predicted income of $10,000 is unlikely t=
o have the same $20,000 standard deviation, since that would imply their ac=
tual income could vary anywhere between =E2=88=92$10,000 and $30,000. (In f=
act, as this shows, in many cases=E2=80=94often the same cases where the as=
sumption of normally distributed errors fails=E2=80=94the variance or stand=
ard deviation should be predicted to be proportional to the mean, rather th=
an constant.) The absence of homoscedasticity is called <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heteroscedasticity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"He=
teroscedasticity">heteroscedasticity</a>. In order to check this assumption=
, a plot of residuals versus predicted values (or the values of each indivi=
dual predictor) can be examined for a "fanning effect" (i.e., increasing or=
 decreasing vertical spread as one moves left to right on the plot). A plot=
 of the absolute or squared residuals versus the predicted values (or each =
predictor) can also be examined for a trend or curvature. Formal tests can =
also be used; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heteroscedastici=
ty" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Heteroscedasticity">Heteroscedasticity</=
a>. The presence of heteroscedasticity will result in an overall "average" =
estimate of variance being used instead of one that takes into account the =
true variance structure. This leads to less precise (but in the case of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_least_squares" title=3D"Ordi=
nary least squares">ordinary least squares</a>, not biased) parameter estim=
ates and biased standard errors, resulting in misleading tests and interval=
 estimates. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_squared_error=
" title=3D"Mean squared error">mean squared error</a> for the model will al=
so be wrong. Various estimation techniques including <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighted_least_squares" title=3D"Weighted least squares"=
>weighted least squares</a> and the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Heteroscedasticity-consistent_standard_errors" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors">heteroscedastici=
ty-consistent standard errors</a> can handle heteroscedasticity in a quite =
general way. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_linear_regre=
ssion" title=3D"Bayesian linear regression">Bayesian linear regression</a> =
techniques can also be used when the variance is assumed to be a function o=
f the mean. It is also possible in some cases to fix the problem by applyin=
g a transformation to the response variable (e.g., fitting the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithm</a> o=
f the response variable using a linear regression model, which implies that=
 the response variable itself has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Log-normal_distribution" title=3D"Log-normal distribution">log-normal dis=
tribution</a> rather than a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal=
_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a>).</li>=
</ul>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Independence_of_Errors_Assumption_for_Linear_=
Regressions.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.w=
ikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Independence_of_Errors_Assumption=
_for_Linear_Regressions.png/500px-Independence_of_Errors_Assumption_for_Lin=
ear_Regressions.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"400" height=3D"234" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1982" data-file-height=3D"1157"></a=
><figcaption>To check for violations of the assumptions of linearity, const=
ant variance, and independence of errors within a linear regression model, =
the residuals are typically plotted against the predicted values (or each o=
f the individual predictors). An apparently random scatter of points about =
the horizontal midline at 0 is ideal, but cannot rule out certain kinds of =
violations such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autocorrelation=
" title=3D"Autocorrelation">autocorrelation</a> in the errors or their corr=
elation with one or more covariates.</figcaption></figure>
<ul><li><b>Independence of errors</b>. This assumes that the errors of the =
response variables are uncorrelated with each other. (Actual <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_independence" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Statistical independence">statistical independence</a> is a strong=
er condition than mere lack of correlation and is often not needed, althoug=
h it can be exploited if it is known to hold.) Some methods such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_least_squares" title=3D"Gener=
alized least squares">generalized least squares</a> are capable of handling=
 correlated errors, although they typically require significantly more data=
 unless some sort of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regularizatio=
n_(mathematics)" title=3D"Regularization (mathematics)">regularization</a> =
is used to bias the model towards assuming uncorrelated errors. <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_linear_regression" title=3D"Bayesian=
 linear regression">Bayesian linear regression</a> is a general way of hand=
ling this issue.</li>
<li><b>Lack of perfect multicollinearity</b> in the predictors. For standar=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_squares" title=3D"Least sq=
uares">least squares</a> estimation methods, the design matrix <i>X</i> mus=
t have full <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Column_rank" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Column rank">column rank</a> <i>p</i>; otherwise perf=
ect <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multicollinearity" title=3D"Mu=
lticollinearity">multicollinearity</a> exists in the predictor variables, m=
eaning a linear relationship exists between two or more predictor variables=
. This can be caused by accidentally duplicating a variable in the data, us=
ing a linear transformation of a variable along with the original (e.g., th=
e same temperature measurements expressed in Fahrenheit and Celsius), or in=
cluding a linear combination of multiple variables in the model, such as th=
eir mean. It can also happen if there is too little data available compared=
 to the number of parameters to be estimated (e.g., fewer data points than =
regression coefficients). Near violations of this assumption, where predict=
ors are highly but not perfectly correlated, can reduce the precision of pa=
rameter estimates (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance_in=
flation_factor" title=3D"Variance inflation factor">Variance inflation fact=
or</a>). In the case of perfect multicollinearity, the parameter vector <i>=
<b>=CE=B2</b></i> will be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-iden=
tifiable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-identifiable">non-identifiable=
</a>=E2=80=94it has no unique solution. In such a case, only some of the pa=
rameters can be identified (i.e., their values can only be estimated within=
 some linear subspace of the full parameter space <b>R</b><sup><i>p</i></su=
p>). See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_least_squares_reg=
ression" title=3D"Partial least squares regression">partial least squares r=
egression</a>. Methods for fitting linear models with multicollinearity hav=
e been developed,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tibshirani-1996_5-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Tib=
shirani-1996-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Efron-2004_6-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note=
-Efron-2004-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hawkins-1973_7-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_not=
e-Hawkins-1973-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jolliffe-1982_8-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite=
_note-Jolliffe-1982-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> some of which require additional assumpti=
ons such as "effect sparsity"=E2=80=94that a large fraction of the effects =
are exactly zero. Note that the more computationally expensive iterated alg=
orithms for parameter estimation, such as those used in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_linear_model" title=3D"Generalized linear=
 model">generalized linear models</a>, do not suffer from this problem.</li=
></ul>
<p>Violations of these assumptions can result in biased estimations of <i><=
b>=CE=B2</b></i>, biased standard errors, untrustworthy confidence interval=
s and significance tests. Beyond these assumptions, several other statistic=
al properties of the data strongly influence the performance of different e=
stimation methods:
</p>
<ul><li>The statistical relationship between the error terms and the regres=
sors plays an important role in determining whether an estimation procedure=
 has desirable sampling properties such as being unbiased and consistent.</=
li>
<li>The arrangement, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilit=
y_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distribution=
</a> of the predictor variables <b>x</b> has a major influence on the preci=
sion of estimates of <i><b>=CE=B2</b></i>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Sampling_(statistics)" title=3D"Sampling (statistics)">Sampling</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_of_experiments" title=
=3D"Design of experiments">design of experiments</a> are highly developed s=
ubfields of statistics that provide guidance for collecting data in such a =
way to achieve a precise estimate of <i><b>=CE=B2</b></i>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Interpretation">Interpretat=
ion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_r=
egression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Interpr=
etation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Anscombe%27s_quartet_3.svg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/e/ec/Anscombe%27s_quartet_3.svg/500px-Anscombe%27s_quartet_3.svg.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"500" height=3D"364" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"990" data-file-height=3D"720"></a><figcaption>The data sets=
 in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anscombe%27s_quartet" titl=
e=3D"Anscombe's quartet">Anscombe's quartet</a> are designed to have approx=
imately the same linear regression line (as well as nearly identical means,=
 standard deviations, and correlations) but are graphically very different.=
 This illustrates the pitfalls of relying solely on a fitted model to under=
stand the relationship between variables.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A fitted linear regression model can be used to identify the relationshi=
p between a single predictor variable <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub> and the r=
esponse variable <i>y</i> when all the other predictor variables in the mod=
el are "held fixed". Specifically, the interpretation of <i>=CE=B2</i><sub>=
<i>j</i></sub> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_val=
ue" title=3D"Expected value">expected</a> change in <i>y</i> for a one-unit=
 change in <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub> when the other covariates are held f=
ixed=E2=80=94that is, the expected value of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Partial_derivative" title=3D"Partial derivative">partial deri=
vative</a> of <i>y</i> with respect to <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>. This is=
 sometimes called the <i>unique effect</i> of <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub> o=
n <i>y</i>. In contrast, the <i>marginal effect</i> of <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i=
></sub> on <i>y</i> can be assessed using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pearson corre=
lation">correlation coefficient</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Simple_linear_regression" title=3D"Simple linear regression">simple li=
near regression</a> model relating only <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub> to <i>y=
</i>; this effect is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_der=
ivative" title=3D"Total derivative">total derivative</a> of <i>y</i> with r=
espect to <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>.
</p><p>Care must be taken when interpreting regression results, as some of =
the regressors may not allow for marginal changes (such as <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dummy_variable_(statistics)" title=3D"Dummy variab=
le (statistics)">dummy variables</a>, or the intercept term), while others =
cannot be held fixed (recall the example from the introduction: it would be=
 impossible to "hold <i>t<sub>i</sub></i> fixed" and at the same time chang=
e the value of <i>t<sub>i</sub></i><sup>2</sup>).
</p><p>It is possible that the unique effect be nearly zero even when the m=
arginal effect is large. This may imply that some other covariate captures =
all the information in <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>, so that once that varia=
ble is in the model, there is no contribution of <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub=
> to the variation in <i>y</i>. Conversely, the unique effect of <i>x</i><s=
ub><i>j</i></sub> can be large while its marginal effect is nearly zero. Th=
is would happen if the other covariates explained a great deal of the varia=
tion of <i>y</i>, but they mainly explain variation in a way that is comple=
mentary to what is captured by <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>. In this case, i=
ncluding the other variables in the model reduces the part of the variabili=
ty of <i>y</i> that is unrelated to <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>, thereby st=
rengthening the apparent relationship with <i>x</i><sub><i>j</i></sub>.
</p><p>The meaning of the expression "held fixed" may depend on how the val=
ues of the predictor variables arise. If the experimenter directly sets the=
 values of the predictor variables according to a study design, the compari=
sons of interest may literally correspond to comparisons among units whose =
predictor variables have been "held fixed" by the experimenter. Alternative=
ly, the expression "held fixed" can refer to a selection that takes place i=
n the context of data analysis. In this case, we "hold a variable fixed" by=
 restricting our attention to the subsets of the data that happen to have a=
 common value for the given predictor variable. This is the only interpreta=
tion of "held fixed" that can be used in an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Observational_study" title=3D"Observational study">observational =
study</a>.
</p><p>The notion of a "unique effect" is appealing when studying a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_system" title=3D"Complex system">=
complex system</a> where multiple interrelated components influence the res=
ponse variable. In some cases, it can literally be interpreted as the causa=
l effect of an intervention that is linked to the value of a predictor vari=
able. However, it has been argued that in many cases multiple regression an=
alysis fails to clarify the relationships between the predictor variables a=
nd the response variable when the predictors are correlated with each other=
 and are not assigned following a study design.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#c=
ite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extensions">Extensions</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regressio=
n&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Extensions"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>Numerous extensions of linear regression have been developed, which allo=
w some or all of the assumptions underlying the basic model to be relaxed.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Simple_and_multiple_linear_=
regression">Simple and multiple linear regression</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Simple and multiple linear regressio=
n"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Linear_regression.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descr=
iption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/=
3a/Linear_regression.svg/500px-Linear_regression.svg.png" decoding=3D"async=
" width=3D"400" height=3D"264" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D=
"438" data-file-height=3D"289"></a><figcaption>Example of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_linear_regression" title=3D"Simple linear re=
gression">simple linear regression</a>, which has one independent variable<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>The simplest case of a single <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
calar_(mathematics)" title=3D"Scalar (mathematics)">scalar</a> predictor va=
riable <i>x</i> and a single scalar response variable <i>y</i> is known as =
<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_linear_regression" title=
=3D"Simple linear regression">simple linear regression</a></i>. The extensi=
on to multiple and/or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_ve=
ctor" title=3D"Euclidean vector">vector</a>-valued predictor variables (den=
oted with a capital <i>X</i>) is known as <b>multiple linear regression</b>=
, also known as <b>multivariable linear regression</b> (not to be confused =
with <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_linear_regres=
sion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multivariate linear regression">multiv=
ariate linear regression</a></i>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-10"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>Multiple linear regression is a generalization of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_linear_regression" title=3D"Simple linear reg=
ression">simple linear regression</a> to the case of more than one independ=
ent variable, and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_case" =
title=3D"Special case">special case</a> of general linear models, restricte=
d to one dependent variable. The basic model for multiple linear regression=
 is
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
