</p><p>Nearly all real-world regression models involve multiple predictors,=
 and basic descriptions of linear regression are often phrased in terms of =
the multiple regression model. Note, however, that in these cases the respo=
nse variable <i>y</i> is still a scalar. Another term, <i>multivariate line=
ar regression</i>, refers to cases where <i>y</i> is a vector, i.e., the sa=
me as <i>general linear regression</i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"General_linear_models">Gene=
ral linear models</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DLinear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: General linear models"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_linear_model" title=
=3D"General linear model">general linear model</a> considers the situation =
when the response variable is not a scalar (for each observation) but a vec=
tor, <b>y</b><sub><i>i</i></sub>. Conditional linearity of <span class=3D"m=
we-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inl=
ine mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://ww=
