</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3a521c6bd48c23e0956f5c3be435c4b551518f15" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.005ex; width:16.769ex; height:3.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle E(=
\mathbf {y} \mid \mathbf {x} _{i})=3D\mathbf {x} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}B}"></sp=
an> is still assumed, with a matrix <i>B</i> replacing the vector <i><b>=CE=
=B2</b></i> of the classical linear regression model. Multivariate analogue=
s of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_least_squares" title=
=3D"Ordinary least squares">ordinary least squares</a> (OLS) and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_least_squares" title=3D"Generali=
zed least squares">generalized least squares</a> (GLS) have been developed.=
 "General linear models" are also called "multivariate linear models". Thes=
e are not the same as multivariable linear models (also called "multiple li=
near models").
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Heteroscedastic_models">Het=
eroscedastic models</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DLinear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit =
section: Heteroscedastic models"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Various models have been created that allow for <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Heteroscedasticity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Heteros=
cedasticity">heteroscedasticity</a>, i.e. the errors for different response=
 variables may have different <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vari=
ance" title=3D"Variance">variances</a>. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighted_least_squares" title=3D"Weighted least squares"=
>weighted least squares</a> is a method for estimating linear regression mo=
dels when the response variables may have different error variances, possib=
ly with correlated errors. (See also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Linear_least_squares_(mathematics)#Weighted_linear_least_squares" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear least squares (mathematics)">Weighted line=
ar least squares</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generali=
zed_least_squares" title=3D"Generalized least squares">Generalized least sq=
uares</a>.) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heteroscedasticity-con=
sistent_standard_errors" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Heteroscedasticity-=
consistent standard errors">Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors</=
a> is an improved method for use with uncorrelated but potentially heterosc=
edastic errors.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Generalized_linear_models">=
Generalized linear models</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DLinear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=
=3D"Edit section: Generalized linear models"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_linear_model" t=
itle=3D"Generalized linear model">Generalized linear model</a> (GLM) is a f=
ramework for modeling response variables that are bounded or discrete. This=
 is used, for example:
</p>
<ul><li>when modeling positive quantities (e.g. prices or populations) that=
 vary over a large scale=E2=80=94which are better described using a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewed_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Skewed distribution">skewed distribution</a> such as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Log-normal_distribution" title=3D"Log-nor=
mal distribution">log-normal distribution</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution" title=3D"Poisson distribution">Poisson=
 distribution</a> (although GLMs are not used for log-normal data, instead =
the response variable is simply transformed using the logarithm function);<=
/li>
<li>when modeling <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Categorical_data=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Categorical data">categorical data</a>, su=
ch as the choice of a given candidate in an election (which is better descr=
ibed using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_distributio=
n" title=3D"Bernoulli distribution">Bernoulli distribution</a>/<a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution" title=3D"Binomial distr=
ibution">binomial distribution</a> for binary choices, or a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Categorical_distribution" title=3D"Categorical di=
stribution">categorical distribution</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Multinomial_distribution" title=3D"Multinomial distribution">multino=
mial distribution</a> for multi-way choices), where there are a fixed numbe=
r of choices that cannot be meaningfully ordered;</li>
<li>when modeling <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinal_data" ti=
tle=3D"Ordinal data">ordinal data</a>, e.g. ratings on a scale from 0 to 5,=
 where the different outcomes can be ordered but where the quantity itself =
may not have any absolute meaning (e.g. a rating of 4 may not be "twice as =
good" in any objective sense as a rating of 2, but simply indicates that it=
 is better than 2 or 3 but not as good as 5).</li></ul>
<p>Generalized linear models allow for an arbitrary <i>link function</i>, <=
i>g</i>, that relates the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" ti=
tle=3D"Mean">mean</a> of the response variable(s) to the predictors: <span =
class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-=
