e response variable.
</p><p>Some common examples of GLMs are:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_regression" title=
=3D"Poisson regression">Poisson regression</a> for count data.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression" title=3D"=
Logistic regression">Logistic regression</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Probit_regression" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Probit reg=
ression">probit regression</a> for binary data.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multinomial_logistic_regressio=
n" title=3D"Multinomial logistic regression">Multinomial logistic regressio=
n</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multinomial_probit" titl=
e=3D"Multinomial probit">multinomial probit</a> regression for categorical =
data.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordered_logit" title=3D"Ordere=
d logit">Ordered logit</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ord=
ered_probit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ordered probit">ordered probit<=
/a> regression for ordinal data.</li></ul>
<p>Single index models<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margi=
n-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span tit=
le=3D"The text near this tag may need clarification or removal of jargon. (=
March 2012)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup> allow some degree o=
f nonlinearity in the relationship between <i>x</i> and <i>y</i>, while pre=
serving the central role of the linear predictor <i>=CE=B2</i>=E2=80=B2<i>x=
</i> as in the classical linear regression model. Under certain conditions,=
 simply applying OLS to data from a single-index model will consistently es=
timate <i>=CE=B2</i> up to a proportionality constant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regr=
ession#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hierarchical_linear_models"=
>Hierarchical linear models</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DLinear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Hierarchical linear models"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hierarchical_linear_models" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hierarchical linear models">Hierarchical linear=
 models</a> (or <i>multilevel regression</i>) organizes the data into a hie=
rarchy of regressions, for example where <i>A</i> is regressed on <i>B</i>,=
 and <i>B</i> is regressed on <i>C</i>. It is often used where the variable=
s of interest have a natural hierarchical structure such as in educational =
statistics, where students are nested in classrooms, classrooms are nested =
in schools, and schools are nested in some administrative grouping, such as=
 a school district. The response variable might be a measure of student ach=
ievement such as a test score, and different covariates would be collected =
at the classroom, school, and school district levels.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Errors-in-variables">Errors=
-in-variables</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DLinear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Errors-in-variables"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Errors-in-variables_model" titl=
e=3D"Errors-in-variables model">Errors-in-variables models</a> (or "measure=
ment error models") extend the traditional linear regression model to allow=
 the predictor variables <i>X</i> to be observed with error. This error cau=
ses standard estimators of <i>=CE=B2</i> to become biased. Generally, the f=
orm of bias is an attenuation, meaning that the effects are biased toward z=
ero.
</p>
