an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dempster%E2%80%93Shafer_theo=
ry" title=3D"Dempster=E2=80=93Shafer theory">Dempster=E2=80=93Shafer theory=
</a>, or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_belief_function"=
 title=3D"Linear belief function">linear belief function</a> in particular,=
 a linear regression model may be represented as a partially swept matrix, =
which can be combined with similar matrices representing observations and o=
ther assumed normal distributions and state equations. The combination of s=
wept or unswept matrices provides an alternative method for estimating line=
ar regression models.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Estimation_methods">Estimat=
ion methods</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Linear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section=
: Estimation methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A large number of procedures have been developed for <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parameter" title=3D"Parameter">parameter</a> estimati=
on and inference in linear regression. These methods differ in computationa=
l simplicity of algorithms, presence of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Closed-form_solution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Closed-form so=
lution">closed-form solution</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Robustness" title=3D"Robustness">robustness</a> with respect to heavy-taile=
d distributions, and theoretical assumptions needed to validate desirable s=
tatistical properties such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cons=
istent_estimator" title=3D"Consistent estimator">consistency</a> and asympt=
otic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficiency_(statistics)" titl=
e=3D"Efficiency (statistics)">efficiency</a>.
</p><p>Some of the more common estimation techniques for linear regression =
are summarized below.
</p>
