<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_estimation_techniques=
">Other estimation techniques</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DLinear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Other estimation techniques"><span>edit</span></a><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Thiel-Sen_estimator.svg" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
e/e9/Thiel-Sen_estimator.svg/250px-Thiel-Sen_estimator.svg.png" decoding=3D=
"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"262" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wi=
dth=3D"2936" data-file-height=3D"3075"></a><figcaption>Comparison of the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theil%E2%80%93Sen_estimator" title=
=3D"Theil=E2=80=93Sen estimator">Theil=E2=80=93Sen estimator</a> (black) an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_linear_regression" title=
=3D"Simple linear regression">simple linear regression</a> (blue) for a set=
 of points with outliers</figcaption></figure>
<ul><li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_linear_regress=
ion" title=3D"Bayesian linear regression">Bayesian linear regression</a></b=
> applies the framework of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesia=
n_statistics" title=3D"Bayesian statistics">Bayesian statistics</a> to line=
ar regression. (See also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_=
multivariate_linear_regression" title=3D"Bayesian multivariate linear regre=
ssion">Bayesian multivariate linear regression</a>.) In particular, the reg=
ression coefficients =CE=B2 are assumed to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random variables</a>=
 with a specified <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prior_distributi=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prior distribution">prior distribution</=
a>. The prior distribution can bias the solutions for the regression coeffi=
cients, in a way similar to (but more general than) <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Ridge_regression" title=3D"Ridge regression">ridge regres=
sion</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lasso_regression" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lasso regression">lasso regression</a>. In addit=
ion, the Bayesian estimation process produces not a single point estimate f=
or the "best" values of the regression coefficients but an entire <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_distribution" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Posterior distribution">posterior distribution</a>, completel=
y describing the uncertainty surrounding the quantity. This can be used to =
estimate the "best" coefficients using the mean, mode, median, any quantile=
 (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantile_regression" title=
=3D"Quantile regression">quantile regression</a>), or any other function of=
 the posterior distribution.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantile_regression" title=
=3D"Quantile regression">Quantile regression</a></b> focuses on the conditi=
onal quantiles of <i>y</i> given <i>X</i> rather than the conditional mean =
of <i>y</i> given <i>X</i>. Linear quantile regression models a particular =
conditional quantile, for example the conditional median, as a linear funct=
ion =CE=B2<sup>T</sup><i>x</i> of the predictors.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mixed_model" title=3D"Mixed=
 model">Mixed models</a></b> are widely used to analyze linear regression r=
elationships involving dependent data when the dependencies have a known st=
ructure. Common applications of mixed models include analysis of data invol=
ving repeated measurements, such as longitudinal data, or data obtained fro=
m cluster sampling. They are generally fit as <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Parametric_statistics" title=3D"Parametric statistics">parametr=
ic</a> models, using maximum likelihood or Bayesian estimation. In the case=
 where the errors are modeled as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
ormal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal</a> random variabl=
es, there is a close connection between mixed models and generalized least =
squares.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed_effects_estimation" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Fixed effects estimation">Fixed effects estimation</a> is an alte=
rnative approach to analyzing this type of data.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_regress=
ion" title=3D"Principal component regression">Principal component regressio=
n</a></b> (PCR)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hawkins-1973_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Hawkins-=
1973-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jolliffe-1982_8-1" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Joll=
iffe-1982-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> is used when the number of predictor variables is l=
arge, or when strong correlations exist among the predictor variables. This=
 two-stage procedure first reduces the predictor variables using <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis" title=3D"Princ=
ipal component analysis">principal component analysis</a>, and then uses th=
e reduced variables in an OLS regression fit. While it often works well in =
practice, there is no general theoretical reason that the most informative =
linear function of the predictor variables should lie among the dominant pr=
incipal components of the multivariate distribution of the predictor variab=
les. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_least_squares_reg=
ression" title=3D"Partial least squares regression">partial least squares r=
egression</a> is the extension of the PCR method which does not suffer from=
 the mentioned deficiency.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least-angle_regression" tit=
le=3D"Least-angle regression">Least-angle regression</a></b><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Efron-2004_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Efron-2004-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is an estimatio=
n procedure for linear regression models that was developed to handle high-=
dimensional covariate vectors, potentially with more covariates than observ=
ations.</li>
<li>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theil%E2%80%93Sen_estim=
ator" title=3D"Theil=E2=80=93Sen estimator">Theil=E2=80=93Sen estimator</a>=
</b> is a simple <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robust_regression=
" title=3D"Robust regression">robust estimation</a> technique that chooses =
the slope of the fit line to be the median of the slopes of the lines throu=
gh pairs of sample points. It has similar statistical efficiency properties=
 to simple linear regression but is much less sensitive to <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outlier" title=3D"Outlier">outliers</a>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Linear_regression#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Other robust estimation techniques, including the <b>=CE=B1-trimmed mea=
n</b> approach, and <b>L-, M-, S-, and R-estimators</b> have been introduce=
d.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regre=
ssion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Applicatio=
ns"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_least_squares#App=
lications" title=3D"Linear least squares">Linear least squares =C2=A7&nbsp;=
Applications</a></div>
<p>Linear regression is widely used in biological, behavioral and social sc=
iences to describe possible relationships between variables. It ranks as on=
e of the most important tools used in these disciplines.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Trend_line">Trend line</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regressio=
n&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Trend line"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trend_estimation" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trend estimation">Trend estimation</a></div>
<p>A <b>trend line</b> represents a trend, the long-term movement in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_series" title=3D"Time series">time =
series</a> data after other components have been accounted for. It tells wh=
ether a particular data set (say GDP, oil prices or stock prices) have incr=
eased or decreased over the period of time. A trend line could simply be dr=
awn by eye through a set of data points, but more properly their position a=
nd slope is calculated using statistical techniques like linear regression.=
 Trend lines typically are straight lines, although some variations use hig=
her degree polynomials depending on the degree of curvature desired in the =
line.
</p><p>Trend lines are sometimes used in business analytics to show changes=
 in data over time. This has the advantage of being simple. Trend lines are=
 often used to argue that a particular action or event (such as training, o=
r an advertising campaign) caused observed changes at a point in time. This=
 is a simple technique, and does not require a control group, experimental =
design, or a sophisticated analysis technique. However, it suffers from a l=
ack of scientific validity in cases where other potential changes can affec=
t the data.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Epidemiology">Epidemiology<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regre=
ssion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Epidemiolo=
gy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Early evidence relating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tobacco=
_smoking" title=3D"Tobacco smoking">tobacco smoking</a> to mortality and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morbidity" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Morbidity">morbidity</a> came from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Observational_studies" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Observational =
studies">observational studies</a> employing regression analysis. In order =
to reduce <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spurious_correlation" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spurious correlation">spurious correlations</a=
> when analyzing observational data, researchers usually include several va=
riables in their regression models in addition to the variable of primary i=
nterest. For example, in a regression model in which cigarette smoking is t=
he independent variable of primary interest and the dependent variable is l=
ifespan measured in years, researchers might include education and income a=
s additional independent variables, to ensure that any observed effect of s=
moking on lifespan is not due to those other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Socioeconomic_status" title=3D"Socioeconomic status">socio-econo=
mic factors</a>. However, it is never possible to include all possible <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confounding" title=3D"Confounding">con=
founding</a> variables in an empirical analysis. For example, a hypothetica=
l gene might increase mortality and also cause people to smoke more. For th=
is reason, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomized_controlled_t=
rial" title=3D"Randomized controlled trial">randomized controlled trials</a=
> are often able to generate more compelling evidence of causal relationshi=
ps than can be obtained using regression analyses of observational data. Wh=
en controlled experiments are not feasible, variants of regression analysis=
 such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Instrumental_variables" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Instrumental variables">instrumental variable=
s</a> regression may be used to attempt to estimate causal relationships fr=
om observational data.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Finance">Finance</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regression&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Finance"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_asset_pricing_model=
" title=3D"Capital asset pricing model">capital asset pricing model</a> use=
s linear regression as well as the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Beta_(finance)" title=3D"Beta (finance)">beta</a> for analyzing=
 and quantifying the systematic risk of an investment. This comes directly =
from the beta coefficient of the linear regression model that relates the r=
eturn on the investment to the return on all risky assets.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Economics">Economics</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regression&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Economics"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Econometrics" title=
=3D"Econometrics">Econometrics</a></div>
<p>Linear regression is the predominant empirical tool in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics">economics</a>. For e=
xample, it is used to predict <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cons=
umption_(economics)" title=3D"Consumption (economics)">consumption spending=
</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed_investment" title=3D"Fixed investment">fixed=
 investment</a> spending, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inventor=
y_investment" title=3D"Inventory investment">inventory investment</a>, purc=
hases of a country's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exports" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Exports">exports</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Krugman=
-2012_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li=
near_regression#cite_note-Krugman-2012-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> spending on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imports" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"I=
mports">imports</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Krugman-2012_25-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Kr=
ugman-2012-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mon=
ey_demand" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Money demand">demand to hold liqu=
id assets</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labour_economics" title=3D"Labour economi=
cs">labor demand</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Smith-2008_27-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Smi=
th-2008-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labor_=
supply" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Labor supply">labor supply</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Smith-2008_27-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Smith-2008-27"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Environmental_science">Envi=
ronmental science</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DLinear_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Environmental science"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Linear regression finds application in a wide range of environmental sci=
ence applications such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_use=
" title=3D"Land use">land use</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-28"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infectious_diseases" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infectious diseases">infectious diseases</a>=
,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_pollution" title=3D"Air pollution">air polluti=
on</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, l=
inear regression can be used to predict the changing effects of car polluti=
on.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One notable exampl=
e of this application in infectious diseases is the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Flattening_the_curve" title=3D"Flattening the curve">flat=
tening the curve</a> strategy emphasized early in the COVID-19 pandemic, wh=
ere public health officials dealt with sparse data on infected individuals =
and sophisticated models of disease transmission to characterize the spread=
 of COVID-19.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Building_science">Building =
science</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLine=
ar_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Bu=
ilding science"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>Linear regression is commonly used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Building_science" title=3D"Building science">building science</a> fi=
eld studies to derive characteristics of building occupants. In a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermal_comfort" title=3D"Thermal comfort=
">thermal comfort</a> field study, building scientists usually ask occupant=
s' thermal sensation votes, which range from -3 (feeling cold) to 0 (neutra=
l) to +3 (feeling hot), and measure occupants' surrounding temperature data=
. A neutral or comfort temperature can be calculated based on a linear regr=
ession between the thermal sensation vote and indoor temperature, and setti=
ng the thermal sensation vote as zero. However, there has been a debate on =
the regression direction: regressing thermal sensation votes (y-axis) again=
st indoor temperature (x-axis) or the opposite: regressing indoor temperatu=
re (y-axis) against thermal sensation votes (x-axis).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regre=
ssion#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Machine_learning">Machine l=
earning</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLine=
ar_regression&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Ma=
chine learning"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>Linear regression plays an important role in the subfield of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial =
intelligence">artificial intelligence</a> known as <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"Machine learning">machine learn=
ing</a>. The linear regression algorithm is one of the fundamental <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supervised_learning" title=3D"Supervised =
learning">supervised machine-learning</a> algorithms due to its relative si=
mplicity and well-known properties.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-34=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DLinear_regression&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Ne=
wton">Isaac Newton</a> is credited with inventing "a certain technique know=
n today as <i>linear regression analysis</i>" in his work on equinoxes in 1=
700, and wrote down the first of the two normal equations of the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_least_squares" title=3D"Ordinary le=
ast squares">ordinary least squares</a> method.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#=
cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-36"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> The Least squares linear regression, as a means of finding a good rough=
 linear fit to a set of points was performed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Adrien-Marie_Legendre" title=3D"Adrien-Marie Legendre">Legend=
re</a> (1805) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauss" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Gauss">Gauss</a> (1809) for the prediction of planeta=
ry movement. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quetelet" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Quetelet">Quetelet</a> was responsible for making the p=
rocedure well-known and for using it extensively in the social sciences.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Stigler-1986_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression#cite_note-Stigler-1986-37"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p>
